snippet.textDisplay:
Ohai! For a change a few personal words. My name is Philipp and I started this channel almost seven years ago – you don’t know my voice but you have heard my words because I write most of our scripts.

Oh boy. This was a hard video to make. Gratitude felt vaguely risky to do as a topic. It has this aura of cheap Instagram hashtag self help stuff.

Some of you will hate this video deeply, and the thought of that made me pretty anxious writing it. Gratitude was not supposed to be a video topic originally. Just like the Nihilism and Loneliness videos, the script was based on personal struggles and part of the process of dealing with them. And so it felt right to make gratitude a video too.

But Kurzgesagt is not a self help channel, so we'll keep this sort of content at roughly one or two per year.

We hope they are helpful to some of you.

If you care for my take on how to practice Gratitude, we made a Kurzgesagt Gratitude journal to combine the science with practical tips. https://shop.kurzgesagt.org/

Please note: You don’t need to buy this or anything else to practice gratitude – you only need a pen, a piece of paper and 5 minutes.

Thank you for watching our videos and reading this comment. Being able to do Kurzgesagt means a lot. To me and the whole team. – Philipp

snippet.textDisplay:
If you prefer an electronic version, you can use things like PDAs, your laptop or PC, or even your cell phone to try it.
I would recommend dusting off an old PDA that you've kept in your junk drawer for the past ten years and seeing if it still works for that option.
Your cell phone or computer will likely have all sorts of associations with work, social pressures, or idle playing attached to it, and coming up with ideas for gratitude might be difficult from this mindset.
But having something specifically for the purpose - an electronic version of that physical journal - would help with that mindset problem.
Any time you're getting this out, you're seeking to find things you're grateful for.
Taking a meditative break from the hustle and bustle of real life, and making a bit of a ritual out of this, might also help.

snippet.textDisplay:
It’s funny because my culture/religion gives importance to gratefulness a lot but somehow I’ve come to associate it with “settling down for worse or less”. It’s clearly not it. I’m not sure what exactly gave me this idea but perhaps it was those that had a resentment towards my culture/religion or the likes of it for the mistakes they’ve done because they weren’t practicing gratefulness in the right sense. Gratefulness isn’t settling down. It is accepting. It doesn’t tell you to move on or not it tells you to despite everything pick that one good thing and appreciate it. Not ignore every other thing or how bad some problems have gotten. But pay attention to the good, give some of your energy to it so it can return to you later.
God I’ve got this wrong for so long.
